{
  "text": "(2) In cases of relatively high cardiac output, USCOM tends to underestimate the real CO value when it is relatively high [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . On the contrary, such a difference does not appear in Su et al.'s research [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . They investigated patients with liver cirrhosis because of their unique hyperdynamic status with high CO values ranging up to 13.6 L/min. They found that even at high CO values, USCOM still reliably measures CO [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
